# Cursor Rule / Skill / Subagent Discipline

If you are editing any file under `.cursor/rules/`, `.cursor/skills/`, or
`.cursor/agents/`, the change is not done until you have ALSO performed
two bookkeeping steps:

## 1. Bump `lastUpdated:` in the file's frontmatter

Every rule/skill/subagent file has a YAML frontmatter block:

```yaml
---
description: ...
alwaysApply: ... or globs: [...]
lastUpdated: YYYY-MM-DD
---
```

When you edit the file, update `lastUpdated:` to today's date. Use the
system `date` command — never guess:

```bash
date +%Y-%m-%d
```

If the file is a brand new rule/skill/subagent and doesn't have
frontmatter yet, add the full block. The required fields are:

| Field | Rules | Skills | Subagents |
|---|---|---|---|
| `description:` | required | required | required |
| `name:` | n/a | required | required |
| `alwaysApply:` | required | n/a | n/a |
| `globs:` | optional (when `alwaysApply: false`) | n/a | n/a |
| `model:` | n/a | n/a | optional |
| `lastUpdated:` | required | required | required |

## 2. Update the matching row in `.cursor/TOOLCHAIN.md`

[`.cursor/TOOLCHAIN.md`](../TOOLCHAIN.md) is the index of every
rule/skill/subagent in the repo, with one row per file. It mirrors the
frontmatter so the agent can read it at session start to see what has
changed in the instruction layer.

When you edit any of these files:

- **Edited an existing file** — update the date column for that row.
  Update the description column too if the frontmatter `description:`
  changed.
- **Added a new file** — add a new row in the right section (Rules,
  Skills, or Subagents). Increment the section count in the section
  heading (e.g. `## Rules (15)` → `## Rules (16)`).
- **Removed a file** — delete the row. Decrement the section count.
- **Renamed a file** — update the link target and the date.

## Why this discipline exists

Without `lastUpdated:` and `TOOLCHAIN.md` discipline:

- An agent reading a rule has no in-context way to tell whether the rule
  is fresh or months old.
- When two rules conflict, the agent has no temporal hint about which is
  newer.
- A cloud agent and a local agent can drift on the instruction layer
  without either knowing.

The same SITE_CHANGELOG and per-component `changelog.json` discipline
exists for the documentation site. This is the agent-toolchain
equivalent.

## Related rules and audits

- [`uds-master-preflight.mdc`](./uds-master-preflight.mdc) Phase -1 —
  the sync-state check that ensures you're not editing on a stale
  baseline.
- [`uds-master-preflight.mdc`](./uds-master-preflight.mdc) Phase 3 step
  11 — the user-facing
  [`uds-docs/docs/pages/cursor-workflows.html`](../../uds-docs/docs/pages/cursor-workflows.html)
  must also be updated when a rule/skill/subagent's purpose changes.
- `scripts/audit-agent-docs-currency.sh` — blocks merge if a
  rule/skill/subagent file exists but isn't referenced on the
  cursor-workflows page (or the reverse).

## Not currently CI-enforced

There is no audit script that fails CI when `lastUpdated:` or
`TOOLCHAIN.md` is stale. Treat it the same as the SITE_CHANGELOG
discipline: a non-negotiable post-edit step. If this becomes a recurring
gap, add a `scripts/audit-toolchain-currency.sh` that diffs git mtime
against `lastUpdated:` and `TOOLCHAIN.md` rows.
